    9	## Proposal 16: Spectral Truncation with Adaptive Zero Selection
    10	
    11	### Verdict: DUPLICATE
    12	
    13	**CLOSED_PATHS matches:**
    14	- "Explicit formula + few zeros" (S5): K^{−0.01} convergence — established that few zeros don't suffice
    15	- "Convergence acceleration of zero sum" (S32): Richardson, Shanks, etc. — errors GROW as N^{0.8–1.0}
    16	- "Hybrid analytic + local sieve" (S32): Optimal hybrid = O(x^{1/2+ε}), matching Lagarias-Odlyzko
    17	- "GRH explicit formula optimal T" (S33): Under GRH, need T = O(√x · log²x) zeros for error < 0.5
    18	- "Riemann-Siegel analog" (S6): = Lagarias-Odlyzko method
    19	- "Zeta zero compression/FMM" (S9): Spectral flatness 0.91, phase catastrophe
    20	
    21	**Failure mode:** EQUIVALENCE. Selecting "resonant" zeros is just reordering the explicit formula summation. The error after K zeros is O(x^{1/2}/K) regardless of selection order. The proposal rediscovers the Lagarias-Odlyzko bound from a different angle.
    22	
    23	**Specific mathematical obstacle:** The explicit formula error term after K zeros is:
    24	  |π(x) − R(x) − Σ_{k=1}^{K} R(x^{ρ_k})| = O(x^{1/2} · T^{−1} · log²T)
    25	where T ~ γ_K. For error < 0.5, need T ~ √x, i.e., K ~ √x · log(√x)/(2π). No reordering changes the total information content needed.
    26	
    27	**What the experiment actually showed:** For n ≥ 500, 1000 zeros insufficient. This is consistent with 6+ prior experiments. The "1–2 zeros suffice for n < 100" observation is a known small-number artifact (R^{−1}(n) is already within 1 of p(n) for small n).
    28	
    29	**Novel content:** None. The "adaptive selection" framing is cosmetically different from "convergence acceleration" (S32) but mathematically identical — both attempt to reorder/select zeros to reduce the count below O(√x).
